blog.name: angelofberlin2000
blog.title: Like a Rose trampled on the ground
blog.description:
In addition to the pain and the exhaustion, he recalled how waiting on the cross between takes became tedious. To fight the boredom, he listened to music on headphones. One particular song called "Above All" (Like a Rose ...) by Michael W. Smith helped him through his most difficult moments.

"It arrived when I was confused and angry. I didn't think I could go on. The song described how Jesus was rejected and alone. That thought took me to a place — it opened an interior door that held me while on the cross," an emotional Caviezel explained. "The experience of feeling rejected and alone as all those around me laughed while drinking their hot coffees, oblivious to what was occurring. Jesus must have felt like this — forsaken, rejected, alone, and despised. It helped me pray in a very deep way — to pray without words, to pray from the heart. The discomfort, the loneliness, the split shoulder, the raw flesh all forced me into the arms of God because I had nowhere else to go for a performance I knew I was unable to create."
Jim Caviezel, Shamelessly Catholic

reasons why it’s scott who picks up mike at the end of my own private idaho:

- there has to be a reason they were staring at each other during the funeral, the scene wouldn’t be written this way for no reason

- it was written in the script that it’s scott

- mike talks about scott in the voiceover at the end

- IMO scott was only convincing himself that he was straight so his dad would accept him more. he is only awakened after his dad’s death

- if it isn’t scott then i’ll lose my mind

title: Babes in Toyland (1986)
body:
Date watched:  16 February 2019

Yeah, look.  I only watched this because of baby Drew Barrymore and baby Keanu Reeves, and then I got halfway into it and I was like, listen, this is not for me, this is a movie meant for very young children and I’m hating this, so then I fast forwarded to the end.

Spoiler alert – it ends happily.

But like, yeah, maybe if you grew up watching this you’re like, “Omg this movie was my childhood!” and that’s cool, but watching this as a 33-year-old woman was kind of like “oh my god it’s literally just people dressed up in bear outfits.”

Yeah, no.

Keanu looked pretty good though, ngl.
